---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const src = 'https://renalcarematters.com/guides/living-with-dialysis.html';
---
<BaseLayout title="Living well on dialysis" description="What dialysis does, how it works, and how to live actively — work, family and all — while on hemodialysis.">
  <article class="section">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:720px">
      <a href="/kidney-health" style="font-weight:700;text-decoration:none">← Kidney Health Hub</a>
      <h1 style="margin-top:14px">Living well on dialysis</h1>
      <p class="lead">Dialysis is not a cure — but it lets you live actively, work, and be with your family.</p>
      <p class="muted" style="font-size:.9rem">Adapted with permission from <a href={src}>renalcarematters.com</a>.</p>

      <h2>What dialysis does for you</h2>
      <p>Three times a week, a machine takes over part of your kidneys' job — removing waste, extra fluid
      and dangerous electrolytes from your blood, and preventing the toxin build-up that would otherwise
      be harmful. It replaces the filtering, not the whole kidney, but it keeps you well enough to carry on
      with your life.</p>

      <h2>How hemodialysis works</h2>
      <p>Your blood passes through a <strong>dialyzer</strong> — often called an artificial kidney — made of
      millions of tiny hollow fibres surrounded by a cleansing fluid. Waste and extra water cross the
      membrane, and clean blood returns to you. Our nurses run and watch this the whole session.</p>

      <div class="notice"><strong>Don't skip sessions.</strong> Each session removes roughly 2 kg of fluid
      and clears toxins. Missing one lets potassium and fluid build up between treatments — which is
      genuinely dangerous. Keeping your schedule is the single most protective thing you can do.</div>

      <h2>Protect your access</h2>
      <p>Your fistula (or access) is your lifeline for every session — keep it clean, and tell us right away
      if it feels different. (See our guide on <a href="/kidney-health/dialysis-access-care">caring for your access</a>.)</p>

      <h2>You can still live your life</h2>
      <p>Many patients keep working, care for their families, and even travel with a little planning. Our
      dietitian and social worker are here to help you fit dialysis around your life, not the other way around.</p>

      <p style="margin-top:20px"><a href="/new-patients#request" class="btn btn--primary">Talk to our team</a></p>
      <p class="muted" style="margin-top:22px;font-size:.9rem">Adapted with permission from
        <a href={src}>renalcarematters.com</a>. Medically reviewed by a nephrologist. Educational only;
        not a substitute for consultation.</p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
